  "description": "So I just read through Theory of the Party from Phil A. Neel and it\u0026rsquo;s weird how outlining how to commodify something is seen as a good contribution to Marxist thought. Like, the piece seems to explain mechanisms that would successfully commodify Mao\u0026rsquo;s mass line into what I might call platformized communism, which might be described as communism that sees its role as practicing its -ism within platforms, not, y\u0026rsquo;know, doing communism. Maybe that\u0026rsquo;d be better named platformalized communism, but the concept is the pertinent part. Also, the just\u0026hellip; affect\u0026hellip; of the writing. Is a lot. Gigantic heapings of rhetorical melancholy are a way to set a mood, which is\u0026hellip; well I guess that is what most introductions are for in academic-style texts, these days, but I don\u0026rsquo;t like it. I\u0026rsquo;m busy imagining history as a \u0026ldquo;carboniferous bonfire,\u0026rdquo; as prompted by the text, I don\u0026rsquo;t know if I can do that and qualify the logic of the arguments, in their own terms.\n",
